parts.text: Hey, so I'm fixing to show you my hair and you tell me how I can do it. I have like rubber bands. I have some hair gel. And that's pretty much it, so.

Alright, let's see what we're working with! If you want to keep it simple, you could try a few small sections with the rubber bands to create a cute pattern, or slick it back into a sleek ponytail with the gel. What kind of look are you going for?
I want one that's, like, cute and, like, kinda cocky, not just, like, boring, you know?
Like, my hair's so short, like, I can't really put it in a ponytail.

No worries! With short hair, you could do a half-up, half-down style. Use the gel to slick the top section back and secure it with a rubber band or two for a playful look. That way, you get something cute and a bit edgy!
I don't know it's hot, so I don't want to leave my hair down like that.

I get that! In that case, you could try a series of small, slicked-back sections with rubber bands, almost like mini ponytails. It keeps your hair off your neck and looks stylish. Plus, it's super easy to do with gel and bands!
Okay, how do I do it?

Alright! First, part your hair into a few horizontal sections from front to back. Then, take each section, apply a bit of gel to smooth it down, and secure it with a rubber band close to your scalp. Repeat for each section, so you end up with a row of small, sleek ponytails. Itâ€™s a cool, sporty look that keeps your hair up and out of the way!
Well, I kind of want to do it on, like, both sides. I want to do two.

Perfect! You can part your hair down the middle and create two sections, one on each side. Slick each side back with gel and secure them with rubber bands near the top or middle of your head. This gives you two sleek mini ponytails or puffs, one on each side, for a balanced and cute style.
Okay, well, I feel like whenever I put my shit up with just the rubber bands like that, like, it looks messy. So how do I do it so it doesn't look fucking messy?

To keep it neat, make sure you comb each section smoothly before you secure it, and use a bit more gel to hold down any flyaways. You can also wrap a small piece of hair around each rubber band to hide it and give a polished look. Just take your time smoothing each section, and it'll look sharp!
Dude, my hair is kind of bald right there, isn't it?

It looks like your part might just be a bit wider there, which is totally normal. You can gently adjust your part or add a bit more gel to help the hair lay evenly. It's definitely not something to worry about!
I'm trying to get my hair parted in the back.

To get a clean part in the back, use the end of a comb or even your finger to feel along your scalp. You can also use a second mirror or your phone camera to check if the line is straight. Take your time and adjust little by little until you're happy with it!
